{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522377"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:44:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:44:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13823"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13823","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13823"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.07,0.56,0.03,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6440"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99328"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6440"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13823"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81713"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2387"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12719"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12720"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34041"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42941"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/99328"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner with a two-week history of a mildly itchy rash under her breasts. She is otherwise in good health, has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are well-demarcated, reddish-brown, slightly scaly patches in the inframammary folds bilaterally (Image). Wood\u0027s lamp examination reveals coral-red fluorescence of the affected areas.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line treatment for this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical fusidate sodium","Oral fluconazole","Topical clotrimazole","Oral tetracycline","Topical hydrocortisone"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with erythrasma, a superficial skin infection caused by \u003Cem\u003ECorynebacterium minutissimum\u003C/em\u003E. The characteristic features include well-demarcated, reddish-brown patches slightly scaley and mildly itchy in intertriginous areas (such as under the breasts, groin or in-between the toes) and coral-red fluorescence under Wood\u0027s lamp examination. The most appropriate first-line treatment for localized erythrasma is \u003Cstrong\u003Etopical fusidate sodium\u003C/strong\u003E. This antibiotic is effective against \u003Cem\u003EC. minutissimum\u003C/em\u003E and would be applied as fusidate sodium 2% ointment topically, twice daily for 14 days, though warn patients that recurrence is common without addressing preventative measures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral fluconazole\u003C/strong\u003E is an antifungal medication used to treat various fungal infections, including candidiasis. While fungal infections can present similarly to erythrasma, the Wood\u0027s lamp findings in this case are not consistent with a fungal etiology and thus oral fluconazole would not have a role in treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical clotrimazole\u003C/strong\u003E is another antifungal agent commonly used for superficial fungal infections such as intertrigo. However, it would not be effective against the bacterial cause of erythrasma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral tetracycline\u003C/strong\u003E can be considered for widespread or recalcitrant cases of erythrasma, but it is not the first-line treatment for localized disease. Topical therapy is generally preferred due to its efficacy and lower risk of side effects compared to systemic antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical hydrocortisone\u003C/strong\u003E is a mild corticosteroid used to reduce inflammation and itching in various skin conditions. While it might provide symptomatic relief, it does not address the underlying bacterial infection and could potentially worsen the condition by suppressing the immune response.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Erythrasma is a superficial skin infection caused by Corynebacterium minutissimum and is frequently found affecting intertriginous areas.","Topical fusidate sodium is an effective first-line treatment for localized erythrasma.","Wood\u0027s lamp examination reveals coral-red fluorescence in erythrasma lesions."],"references":["Ricardo J, Sebaratnam, D. Erythrasma. In: Australasian College of Dermatologists [online]. 2019. Available at: https://www.dermcoll.edu.au/atoz/erythrasma/","Teixeria F, Torres, T. Pruiritic erythematous plaque in skin folds. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2021;50(5). Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2021/may/pruritic-erythematous-plaque-in-the-skin-folds"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81713"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13823"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20770"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20770"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4nRosICCUhzhxINa7Z8SC0AuBYp8CZ.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4nRosICCUhzhxINa7Z8SC0AuBYp8CZ.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/81713"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-20T14:23:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-20T14:24:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6440"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99328"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms"